ponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EOn urinary dipstick analysis, \u003Cstrong\u003Eleukocyte esterase\u003C/strong\u003E is an enzyme produced by white blood cells and indicates pyuria (presence of white blood cells in urine). This is a key marker for urinary tract infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtein\u003C/strong\u003E indicates proteinuria which may suggest glomerular disease or other kidney pathology\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood\u003C/strong\u003E indicates haematuria which can occur with infection, stones, or malignancy\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose\u003C/strong\u003E in urine suggests hyperglycaemia (as in diabetes mellitus) or renal tubular dysfunction\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENitrite\u003C/strong\u003E is produced when bacteria convert urinary nitrate to nitrite, indicating bacteriuria but not inflammation\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA positive leukocyte esterase test suggests inflammation, while nitrites indicate bacterial presence. Both tests together provide better diagnostic accuracy for urinary tract infection than either test alone.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Leukocyte esterase on urinary dipstick indicates the presence of white blood cells (pyuria) in urine","Nitrites indicate bacterial presence through conversion of urinary nitrates","Urinary dipstick testing provides rapid screening for both inflammation (leukocyte esterase) and infection (nitrites) in suspected urinary tract infection"],"references":["Devill\u00e9 WL, Yzermans JC, van Duijn NP, Bezemer PD, van der Windt DA, Bouter LM. The urine dipstick test useful to rule out infections. A meta-analysis of the accuracy. BMC Urol. 2004 Jun 2;4:4. doi: 10.1186/1471-2490-4-4. PMID: 15175113; PMCID: PMC434513.","Lim WH, Choi EK, Han KD, Rhee TM, Lee HJ, Lee SR, Kang SH, Cha MJ, 